<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12054d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12054d">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12054d"> 54(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> burning whisky</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">La foudre qui, cette ann&eacute;e-l&agrave;, tomba sur la tour &laquo;dont la pyramide, ainsi que le constate avec orgueil l&apos;annaliste Dom Huynes, &eacute;tait la plus haute du royaume&raquo;, mit le feu au clocher et f&icirc;t couler le m&eacute;tal &agrave; flots &laquo;fluit aes rivis&raquo;. Cependant, Jean de Surtainville, sur l&apos;ordre du fermier g&eacute;n&eacute;ral et de l&apos;abb&eacute; Fran&ccedil;ois de Joyeuse &laquo;f&icirc;t refaire le clocher et fondre quatre cloches o&ugrave; fut mis le nom de l&apos;abb&eacute;&raquo;. <br><font color="green">[The lightning that, that year, struck the tower &ldquo;of which the pyramid, as the annalist Dom Huynes proudly boasts, was the highest of the kingdom&rdquo; and set fire to the belfry and melted the metal in flows &ldquo;fluit aes rivis&rdquo;. Yet Jean de Surtainville, on the order of the tax collector and abbot Fran&ccedil;ois de Joyeuse, &ldquo;had the bell tower restored and made four bells on which was put the name of the abbot.&rdquo;]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="SMIN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#SMIN"><cite title="source">Le Mont Saint-Michel Inconnu</cite></a> (1912) 91</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
